A rare black rhino, prominently identified by ‘Faru Rajabu’ has died aged 43, Tanzania National Parks Authority (TANAPA) announced on Monday. He was aged. The authority said in a statement. Most rhinoceros live to about 40 years old and his father, Faru John died in 2015 aged 47. His death comes a few months after Tanzania’s President Samia Suluhu Hassan stepped up pursuit to get him a cow ‘a female rhino’ from the neighbouring Kenya. The late Dr. John Magufuli once congratulated him for his efforts to increase the number of rhinos to 140 in the Serengeti National Park. A statement from the Tanapa detailed that Faru Rajabu died last night and his remains will be conserved in accordance with conservation regulations. Faru Rajabu is survived by several calves, grand calves and great-grand calves, a statement from TANAPA’s Senior Assistant Commissioner in charge of Corporate Communications Mr Pascal Shelutete said. Faru Rajabu was born in the Ngorongoro area in 1979, and in 1993, was moved to the Serengeti National Park.